{
  "root_cause": "The CUDA IPC pool handle cache is disabled by default (SGLANG_USE_IPC_POOL_HANDLE_CACHE=0). Under concurrent multimodal load, each request opens a fresh IPC handle to the MmItemMemoryPool storage on the sender GPU. When the pool is recycled and a chunk is freed, the pool's CUDA IPC handle (storage._share_cuda_()) is reused but the underlying device memory is freed/recycled. Without caching opened UntypedStorage instances, the receiver opens a stale pointer to memory that has been reallocated, causing HIP error: invalid device pointer on reconstruct_on_target_device. The pool recycler thread periodically returns chunks to available_chunks, and under high concurrency the timing window between free and reconstruct means the receiver gets a handle pointing to newly-allocated (wrong) memory.",
  "fix": "Set SGLANG_USE_IPC_POOL_HANDLE_CACHE=1 to enable caching of opened CUDA IPC pool handles (UntypedStorage instances) in the MmItemMemoryPool. With caching enabled, once an IPC handle is opened it is stored in _pool_storage_cache and reused on subsequent reconstruct calls, avoiding stale pointer issues from repeated open/close cycles of the same handle. Also increases SGLANG_MM_FEATURE_CACHE_MB from 1024 to 2048 to prevent pool fragmentation under concurrency.",
  "evidence": "[2026-07-16 12:50:59 TP1] Failed to deserialize from CUDA IPC handle (HIP error: invalid device pointer ... reconstruct_on_target_device (cuda_ipc_transport_utils.py)\ntorch.AcceleratorError: HIP error: invalid device pointer\nSIGQUIT received. ... It usually means one child failed."
}
